tasks.prompt:
Consider five points in the Euclidean plane:
A = (0, 0), B = (2, 0), C = (2, 2), D = (0, 2), and E = (1, 1).

A Euclidean Steiner tree on a finite set of points (terminals) is a connected graph of minimum total edge length whose vertices include all terminals and possibly additional Steiner points. Every Steiner point has degree exactly three, and the three incident edges meet at pairwise 120° angles.

Prove that the minimal Steiner tree on {A, B, C, D, E} has total length exactly 2 + 2√3. Your proof must:
(i) Explicitly determine the coordinates of every Steiner point;
(ii) Verify that the angle condition (120°) holds at each Steiner point;
(iii) Prove that the terminal E = (1, 1) lies on a Steiner edge of the four-point tree for {A, B, C, D}, and explain why this implies the five-point Steiner tree has the same topology and total length as the four-point tree;
(iv) Conclude that no alternative topology can yield a shorter total length.
